<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="gcp-billing-cost">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>infrastructure-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Configure GCP billing accounts, budget alerts at multiple thresholds, BigQuery billing exports, and cost allocation labels for per-team chargeback and spend optimization.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>gcp</tag>
      <tag>billing</tag>
      <tag>cost-management</tag>
      <tag>budgets</tag>
      <tag>cost-allocation</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>infra</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="gcp-resource-hierarchy"/>
      <ref slug="gcp-org-policies"/>
      <ref slug="gcp-overview-cli"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>GCP Billing and Cost Management</title>

    <summary>GCP billing is structured around billing accounts linked to projects, with costs attributed via resource labels. Budget alerts at 50%, 90%, and 100% thresholds prevent surprise overspend. BigQuery billing exports enable custom dashboards and per-team chargeback via label-based queries. Labels are the only mechanism for cost allocation — enforce them from day one via org policy.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>GCP costs grow silently without proactive controls. A project created without budget alerts can run up thousands of dollars before anyone notices. BigQuery billing exports with a consistent label taxonomy (env, team, cost_center) enable finance to chargeback costs to teams without manual sorting. Committed use discounts (CUDs) require capacity planning — the analysis tooling built on billing exports pays for itself.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up billing for a new GCP organization, project, or environment.</item>
        <item>Implementing cost chargeback by team, cost center, or application.</item>
        <item>Configuring budget alerts before launching production workloads.</item>
        <item>Analyzing and optimizing existing GCP spend (rightsizing, CUDs, storage class).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Personal sandbox projects with minimal spend — a single $10/month alert is sufficient; full export pipeline is over-engineering.</item>
        <item>Network cost analysis (egress, interconnect) — those require Traffic Analytics and billing exports combined with VPC Flow Logs.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="billing-structure">
      <p>GCP billing components and their roles:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Billing Account — pays for all linked projects; uses single currency; tied to a payment method via Payments Profile.</item>
        <item>Payments Profile — links billing account to the payment method (credit card, invoice).</item>
        <item>Budgets — alert at configurable spend thresholds; can trigger Pub/Sub actions.</item>
        <item>Cost Allocation — achieved via resource labels and the folder/project hierarchy in billing reports.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every production project MUST have a budget configured with alert thresholds at 50%, 90%, and 100% of the monthly spend target. Alerts MUST route to a monitored notification channel (email group or Pub/Sub).</statement>
        <rationale>Without budget alerts, cost anomalies (runaway VMs, data egress spikes, accidental BigQuery full table scans) go undetected until the monthly bill. Multi-threshold alerts give early warning before overspend is irrecoverable.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Billing exports MUST be enabled to BigQuery for all production billing accounts. The export dataset must be queried via scheduled queries or Looker Studio to produce per-team cost reports at least monthly.</statement>
        <rationale>The GCP console billing UI does not support custom cost allocation or chargeback. BigQuery exports are the only way to query costs by label, folder, or project combination at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="budget-configuration">
      <example type="good" title="Budget alert via gcloud">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Create budget with three alert thresholds
gcloud billing budgets create \
  --billing-account=BILLING_ACCOUNT_ID \
  --display-name="Project Monthly Budget" \
  --budget-amount=1000USD \
  --threshold-rules="percent=0.5,basis=current-spend" \
  --threshold-rules="percent=0.9,basis=current-spend" \
  --threshold-rules="percent=1.0,basis=current-spend" \
  --filter-projects="projects/PROJECT_ID" \
  --notifications-rule="monitoringNotificationChannels=CHANNEL_ID"
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Terraform billing budget module">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
# modules/billing/main.tf
resource "google_monitoring_notification_channel" "email" {
  for_each = toset(var.alert_emails)

  project      = var.project_id
  display_name = "Budget Alert - ${each.value}"
  type         = "email"

  labels = {
    email_address = each.value
  }
}

resource "google_billing_budget" "project" {
  billing_account = var.billing_account
  display_name    = "Budget - ${var.project_id}"

  budget_filter {
    projects = ["projects/${var.project_number}"]
  }

  amount {
    specified_amount {
      currency_code = "USD"
      units         = tostring(var.budget_amount)
    }
  }

  threshold_rules {
    threshold_percent = 0.5
    spend_basis       = "CURRENT_SPEND"
  }

  threshold_rules {
    threshold_percent = 0.75
    spend_basis       = "CURRENT_SPEND"
  }

  threshold_rules {
    threshold_percent = 0.9
    spend_basis       = "CURRENT_SPEND"
  }

  threshold_rules {
    threshold_percent = 1.0
    spend_basis       = "CURRENT_SPEND"
  }

  all_updates_rule {
    monitoring_notification_channels = [
      for channel in google_monitoring_notification_channel.email : channel.id
    ]
    disable_default_iam_recipients = false
  }
}
]]></code>
        <note>Parameterize budget_amount and alert_emails per environment. Use a billing module called from the project factory.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Single 100% threshold budget alert only.</description>
        <reason>By the time the 100% alert fires, the spend is already at the budget limit. Multi-threshold alerts (50%, 90%) give time to investigate and cap before the budget is exhausted.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No billing exports configured; relying on the GCP console billing UI for cost reporting.</description>
        <reason>The console UI cannot filter by resource labels, aggregate across folders, or support chargeback queries. BigQuery exports are mandatory for any organization with more than one team or project.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cost-allocation">
      <p>Cost allocation relies entirely on consistent resource labels. Without labels, BigQuery billing exports cannot attribute costs to teams or cost centers.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>All projects MUST have env, team, and cost_center labels. All major resources (VMs, GKE node pools, Cloud SQL instances, buckets) MUST inherit or carry the same labels. Enforce via org policy custom constraint (custom.requireProjectLabels).</statement>
        <rationale>Labels are propagated to billing export line items. A missing label on a VM means that VM's cost appears as unattributed in chargeback reports — the team is not charged and no one investigates the spend.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Label taxonomy for cost allocation">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
Required Labels (enforced via org policy):
  env: prod|staging|dev
  team: platform|backend|frontend|data
  cost_center: cc-NNN
  managed_by: terraform|manual

Optional Labels:
  app: application-name
  component: api|web|worker
  owner: team-email
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="BigQuery billing export query — cost by team">
        <code lang="sql"><![CDATA[
-- Monthly cost by team from BigQuery billing export
SELECT
  labels.value AS team,
  SUM(cost) AS total_cost,
  SUM(cost) + SUM(IFNULL((SELECT SUM(c.amount) FROM UNNEST(credits) c), 0)) AS net_cost
FROM `billing_dataset.gcp_billing_export_v1_XXXXXX_XXXXXX_XXXXXX`
CROSS JOIN UNNEST(labels) AS labels
WHERE labels.key = 'team'
  AND DATE(usage_start_time) >= DATE_TRUNC(CURRENT_DATE(), MONTH)
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 DESC;
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="billing-setup-checklist">
      <checklist>
        <check>Billing account configured and linked to organization.</check>
        <check>Budget alerts set at 50%, 90%, and 100% thresholds for each project.</check>
        <check>Billing exports to BigQuery enabled for production billing account.</check>
        <check>Cost allocation labels (env, team, cost_center) defined and enforced via org policy.</check>
        <check>Committed use discounts evaluated for stable workloads running &gt;= 12 months.</check>
        <check>Billing reports configured by folder/project in Console or Looker Studio.</check>
        <check>Rightsizing recommendations reviewed monthly (GCP recommender API).</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="Design cost management strategy">
        <![CDATA[
Design cost management strategy for GCP [ORGANIZATION/PROJECT]:

Context:
- Monthly budget: [amount]
- Teams/cost centers: [list]
- Chargeback requirements: [describe]
- Existing spending: [current patterns]

Requirements:
1. Budget alert configuration
2. Cost allocation via labels
3. BigQuery billing export setup
4. Looker Studio dashboard
5. Committed use discount analysis
6. Rightsizing recommendations

Deliverables:
- Budget configuration per project
- Label taxonomy for cost allocation
- Dashboard queries
- Cost optimization checklist
]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="Optimize GCP costs">
        <![CDATA[
Analyze and optimize GCP costs for [PROJECT/ORGANIZATION]:

Current Spending:
- Monthly cost: [amount]
- Top services: [list]
- Growth trend: [describe]

Optimization Areas:
1. Idle resources identification
2. Rightsizing opportunities
3. Committed use discounts
4. Preemptible/Spot VM opportunities
5. Storage class optimization
6. Network egress reduction

Output:
- Potential savings by category
- Implementation steps
- Risk assessment
- Monitoring setup post-optimization
]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

